etymologies: late 16th century; earliest use found in Thomas Hughes (fl. 1571–1623), lawyer and playwright. From mis- + content. Compare earlier miscontent, miscontent

etymologies: late 15th century; earliest use found in John Skelton (c1460–1529), poet. From mis- + content. Compare Middle French mescontent; also Italian †miscontento. Compare slightly later miscontent and slightly earlier miscontenting

definitions: Not content; discontented, dissatisfied; ill-pleased. In early use frequently with of, with.
